Title: Cribsheet: A Data-Driven Guide to Better, More Relaxed Parenting, from Birth to Preschool
Author: Emily Oster
My Review: Light reading. That is not to say that it's a bad book; only that if you are hungry for a more in-depth scientific analysis, this might not be the exact book you should be opening. Good as a gentle introduction to all things baby-related, though. And it's refreshing to see randomized clinical trials held on the pedestal they deserve to be held, especially in a parenting book.

Title: The Secret History
Author: Donna Tartt
My Review:
If someone can, for ten tireless years, work and believe in the spirit of what The Secret History is, as Donna Tartt did, then I call that a good writer of a good book. The atmosphere, the ideas, the characters, their overarching story - they all follow a red thread, to which all are coherently connected. And I like to think that their evolution and their demise - are all painfully linked to the opening paragraph of the book:

“Does such a thing as 'the fatal flaw,' that showy dark crack running down the middle of a life, exist outside literature? I used to think it didn't. Now I think it does. And I think that mine is this: a morbid longing for the picturesque at all costs.”

Title: Hotel du Lac
Author: Anita Brookner
My Review: Why do you lend your ear to unworthy characters? Why do you slant your pen in the direction of tiny, forgettable memories? Why don't you look inwards and see more of the beauty? I heard myself asking these questions, as I went through the book, and I wonder if that is indeed the essence of it all — the sin of not being yourself. Although I revelled in the beautiful writing, there were times when I reproached her for too much of the superficial seeping into the book, in spite of herself, in spite of the entire idea of the book.

Author: Orlando Figes

Title: Summer
Author: Karl Ove Knausgård
My Review: I've had an immense thirst for summer. Endless days and endless light; the peace you can only find in the shapes of green leaves and small grass. The stillness of a dimly-lit window, watched from afar. I am happy to say I found all of this here, enveloped in a comforting unpretentiousness, but meditative enough to still be stimulating.

Author: Karl Ove Knausgård
Additional Authors: Ingvild Burkey, Vanessa Baird, Karl Ove Knausgaard
My Review: There is potential; there are occasional glimpses of wit, and at times it gleams with intimacy. But they are just too sparse. The mundane is overpraised; so much so that some chapters, themselves, become mundane and unremarkable. I suppose that is the risk we run when writing about the mundane, after all.

Title: Love, Money, and Parenting: How Economics Explains the Way We Raise Our Kids
Author: Matthias Doepke
My Review: Academic goodness, succeeding in analysing a particular topic - parenting styles and economics, whilst skilfully keeping aspects of history, religion and culture as a backdrop. Appropriately enough, you get the entire picture; and thus, a deeper understanding of the choices that parents make and need to make in relation to their children. While the writing can sometimes feel dry, I loved how thorough the analysis was, up until the very end.

Title: The Works: Anatomy of a City
Author: Kate Ascher
My Review:
A gentle introduction to the inner workings of cities, with beautiful and equally useful illustrations.

I like to believe that the way New York functions as a city has inspired other places around the world as well; but that's for me to find out next. So if the topic of "cities-as-a-live-organism" fascinate you - as they fascinate me, this book will definitely not quench your thirst; it will only make you want more.

Title: Packing for Mars: The Curious Science of Life in the Void
Author: Mary Roach
My Review: Although the topic is infinitely interesting, and spins on a new take about space exploration and what being an astronaut means, I found the writing style a little too journalistic for my taste, especially given the subject. The bits of trivia about space in general, biology and how people behave in small, confined spaces surely did open an appetite for more like this.
